<DOC><DOCNO> AP890516-0031 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0319EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Glance     05-16 0247</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bush-Glance,250</SECOND><HEAD>Bush Anti-Crime Proposals at a Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Bush-Crime</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are main provisions of the$1.2 billion anti-crime package President Bush proposed Monday.   Bush would:   _Make permanent a ban on imported semiautomatic assault rifles _if the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms rules they are notfor sport _ but allow U.S. manufacturers to keep making and sellingsuch weapons.   _Ban semiautomatic ammunition clips of more than 15 rounds.   _Double the current five-year minimum sentence for using asemiautomatic firearm in a crime.   _Block the practice of dropping many gun-use charges throughplea bargaining.   _Spend $1 billion for new prison construction; identifygovernment properties and facilities for conversion to jails andprisons.   _Execute people who commit such federal offenses as murder forhire, killings by federal prisoners serving life sentences,terrorist murders of American citizens, and murders of hostages.Also allow executions for such crimes as treason and espionageunder provisions now in disuse because statutes do not satisfySupreme Court guidelines.   _Authorize 825 new federal agents and staff in the Bureau ofAlcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the U.S. Marshals Service and theFBI.   _Amend the Armed Career Criminal statute to include juvenileconvictions when deciding whether someone is a habitual criminaland thus subject to an enhanced sentence.   _Expand the existing ban on firearm sales to people convicted ofcertain violent crimes, to cover anyone convicted of violentmisdemeanor offenses.   _Add 1,600 positions in federal prosecutors' offices.</TEXT></DOC>